node.text:
Here’s a shot that shows some of what went into our crystal cannabonsai 🔮

it can get a bit hectic with more branches haha so this one year old cannabonsai actually spent most of the time looking a bit wild like this

some of our bonsai only need a few stakes or coils but for this one we worked with a central trunk and horizontal branches with a few compound curves so it needed a few more than usual 

photoperiods are great for styles that require a bit more time to develop out, something to consider when picking strain/style pairs

loosening and re-coiling every few weeks will also help avoid leaving impressions on the branches

we’ll usually anchor the coil to the branch’s base, in this case the trunk itself, before extending outward to wrap around the length of the branch

once the coil is in place you can bend the group together at a few points to create multiple curves/profiles on each branch, while considering their distance from others to create open spaces 

let us know what you want to hear more about, we’re always open to making new resources on our site! 

🌴🌴🌴

#cannabonsai

node.text:
Something we did back on this crystal was set the selenite base directly above a drainage hole so that we could illuinate the crystal from below! 💡💡

And yes haha selenite does degrade in water but very slowly - our crystal cannabonsai here was over a year old and the crystal base hardly changed!

node.text:
We’ve been taking a bit of a break since shopify shut down our payments a few months ago to focus on rebuilding our site and it’s finally ready! 

We wanted to start our new blog off by sharing a bit more about us. At the heart of it, cannabonzai is a cross-cultural project — one half of us is Taiwanese and the other half french/scottish/something haha 

We try to do everything from a place of respect and i think it wouldn’t look the same if it didn’t come from an authentic place of our experiences

Both of our backgrounds are in art and design so we’ve really enjoyed learning how do all of this from the photography to the videos, to book making and now site builds🪚🤘

It was tough working on this project while juggling jobs but it’s been awesome to be able to connect with many of you. It was and still is vulnerable to put our thoughts and work out there but the response has been really motivating so thank you if you’re reading this — the bumps on the road might have been harder to bounce back from without it! 

If you’re interested in reading a little bit more of our story, check out our brief ‘about us’ blog on our new site at cannabonsai.com or as they say “link in bio” haha

-S & P

Also shoutout to homie in QC that talked to my cousin in the bonsai section of a shop🪴🪴🤝

node.text:
Mt.Zkittles - smell the rainbow @fastbuds_genetics

We wanted this cannabonsai to be a relatively easy style while we were setting up a new box and light so this is a simple root-on-rock over a small town we put together

Last year we grew on a 3d printed city to try out the concept, giving us a handful of aged sandstone buildings at the end of the grow. So for this round we’re reusing the buildings by separating them and carving the shapes of the rock base into the bottom so they’d fit flush to the rock

Our new website will be ready this Friday with a blog section and some other fun things to check out! In our mini-hiatus, we’ve been experimenting with new styles and techniques and cookin up some exciting collabs. Can’t wait to show y’all

node.text:
This is the last video of our Manhattan bonsai before she got sick. Here we pull secondary branches down to build out a flat layer of foliage over the sandstone buildings.

We started by testing how brittle the branches are and softening them by pinching and bending prior to coiling. We wrapped the coil around the branch being careful of node placement before bending the whole branch with coils down fully into position. Even if the branch is a little stiff, coiling will control curves well and help branches to thicken and set into shape, eventually holding still without coils.

It was tough to put new seeds in the ground after losing a few one-year old bonsai all at once but we’ve finally got a few new bonsai coming soon!

Ever wonder what off-gassing looks like?

Dropped a live flower in resin to visualize gas expansion

As it released gases, enough pressure was generated to push outward against the curing resin, producing these air pockets

Can’t get enough of these shapes 🔬 few macros to come

node.text:
Here’s a close up of the flowers from the graft experiment on our old moon bonsai, which was half Purple Trainwreck, half Gelato

We initially chose these two strains because we hoped the color of the Purple Trainwreck would contrast with that of the Gelato, and while there was a bit of purple in both, the main difference was in the cola thickness and leaf width

It seems like the graft didn’t disrupt their different flowering lengths, because one still matured a little faster than the other, showing ambers earlier on by a week or so despite being on a rootstock with different genes

Can you tell which colas are Purple Trainwreck and which are Gelato?🧐

More grafts in the works!

If you’re interested in grafting check out the 🐐 @lightaddict420

node.text:
Another quick time-lapse of the crystal’s transplant —

we posted this as an 8 minute walkthru at the time, but this tells most of the story in a few seconds and helps compare to the end result

a few people have asked why we loosen and clean the roots when the soil is dry instead of using running water or spray, and while it is a good technique to clean them, we find that it can get a bit difficult to untangle and separate specific root groupings for placement when they’re wet

also wonder if it disturbs the finer hairs that you’ll see here are still clinging on to tiny bits of soil. We’ve had a few get stressed after fully cleaning them with water, but this is just our typical approach and we’ve actually seen great results from other cannabonsai growers that flush their roots clean with water before transplanting onto their base medium

Many mentioned that the selenite would dissolve because it’s water soluble - it has been a year and we haven’t seen much change, does anyone know long selenite/gypsum crystals take to properly dissolve?

Let us know what topics/timelapses you’d like to see in our upcoming round of bonsai!
